\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Discussion of Homeo Robotic Experiments and expected results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Stefano Franchi
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
A note to myself detailing the homeostatic architectures of the different
 vehicle involved in the Homeo robotic experiments, together with expected
 results (and, eventually, actual results)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This series of notes discusses the various experiments to be carried with
 Homeo joined to a simulated robotic environment (Webots).
 Its main goal is to clearly identify, for each experimental setup, the
 environmental setup (the Webots world, and what it stands for), the homeostatic
 architecture (number and type of units), the expected behaviors, and, if
 possible, the expected dynamics.
 It will start with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

simplest possible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 homeostatic creature: a Braitenberg-like type 1 vehicle with one sensory
 opening to the world and one actuator (motor).
 With some approximation, it may resemble a biological agent carrying out
 chemotaxis.
 These notes will then discuss Brainteberg-like type 2 vehicles carrying
 out phototaxis, and multimodal creatures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Type-1 taxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Environment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a flat world with no obstacle and no perturbations (i.e.
 no buffeting from external forces such as those that a living organism
 carrying out chemotaxis may experience).
 The environment presents a stimulus gradient of an unspecified kind which
 is simulated by one or more light sources.
 The organism/vehicle has 
\emph on
one 
\emph default
sensory input tuned to the stimulus (i.e.
 a light sensor) and one actuator allowing one dimensional translation (i.e.
 a motor connected to a wheel that can spin either forward or backward).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Homeostatic setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in other notes, there are two possible setups: a 2 unit setup
 with a sensor unit and a motor/actuator unit and a 1 unit setup with only
 a motor unit connected to a sensory interface (these two setups corresponds
 to Ashby second and, respectively, first experiment in 
\emph on
Design for a Brain
\emph default
).
 The main difference between the two setups is that the 2-unit architecture
 allows 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

input-modulation,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 so to speak: the organism may change its sensitivity to the external stimulus
 by changing the parameter controlling the the percentage of the input that
 is transmitted to the other unit.
 No such input modulation exists for the alternative setup.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overall features of the described setups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
