\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us analyze the behavior of the vehicle by first reducing it to its simplest
 possible setup, and then gradually adding additional features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Simplest setup: no self-connections
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If we remove from the setup in figure 
\begin_inset Flex ShortXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2-unit-setup-for-type-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 the self-connections (
\begin_inset Formula $S\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\rightarrow M$
\end_inset

), we obtain an approximation of a Braitenberg type-1 vehicle (see point
 below for why it is an approximation).
 This vehicle will transmit directly its input to to its output motor.
 If the 
\emph on
perceived
\emph default
 stimulus is directly proportional to the stimulus source, it will therefore
 move 
\emph on
away 
\emph default
from it.
 If on the contrary, the perceived stimulus is 
\emph on
inversely
\emph default
 proportional to the source, it will move 
\emph on
toward 
\emph default
it.
 Put it differently, the direct proportional setup vehicle will 
\emph on
climb down
\emph default
 a gradient, while its inversely proportional counterpart will 
\emph on
climb up 
\emph default
a gradient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Why units without self-loops only approximate Braitenberg architectures
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Because a HomeoUnit is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Newtonian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 object: the input is a force (torque) that changes its velocity, not its
 position.
 A true Braitenberg vehicle would have to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aristotelian,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with input affecting its position, not its velocity.
 As a Newtonian physical laws approximate Aristotelian laws whenever friction
 forces are high, and the equivalent of friction forces in Homeo units is
 the viscosity of the medium the needle moves in, it follows that by increasing
 the viscosity we would come closer to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Braitenberg setup.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Actually, there are two parameters affecting needle's physical movement:
 viscosity and density.
 Both need to be tuned to obtain the desired 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aristotelian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 result.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another important difference between the Homeo setup and Braitenberg's.
 The range of values of a Homeo unit is centered around 0, whereas the range
 of values of a Braitenberg's vehicle is always positive.
 If, as in the current setup, the Homeo unit's is directly transmitted to
 the output (just scaled), then the robot's actuator may receive both positive
 and negative values, which would translate in the robot moving forward
 or, respectively, backward.
 A truly analogous Braitenberg vehicle would convert the value of the motor
 unit to positive actuator commands instead of simply scaling them to the
 appropriate range.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Expected observable behavior
\emph default
s.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
