\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Images/Braiten-1-gradient.pdf
	lyxscale 150

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex ShortLabel
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Brait-like-type-1-gradient"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Braitenberg-like Type 1 vehicle in an environmental stimulus gradient.
 The spherical gradient identified the environmental stimulus, centered
 on the red dot.
 The external green circle represent the minimum possible stimulus.
 This will be equal to zero in a traditional Braitenberg vehicle, whereas
 it will be negative and equal to the minimum possible value (which is always
 negative) of the sensory unit in the standard Homeo setup.
 The red circle indicates the threshold value equal to exactly half the
 value of the stimulus, which is equivalent to exactly 0 in the standard
 Homeo setup.
 Notice that the red circle may not be halfway between the center of the
 gradient and the green line, and its position depends on the chosen stimulus's
 decay rule (which, for light, is inversely quadratic).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the perceived stimulus is directly proportional to the input stimulus,
 we would observe the following behaviors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A true Braitenberg vehicle---and a true 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aristotelian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Homeo unit with always positive actuator commands, as discussed above---will
 keep moving straight until its input is zero (or sufficiently close to
 zero, tasking into account that the Webots software does provide some simulatio
n for frictional forces acting on the robot).
 The robot will keep moving until the gradient's value is 0, where it'll
 stop.
 If the gradient never reaches zero, it'll keep moving forward (at least,
 until the sensory input's falls below the minimal threshold needed to overcome
 frictional forces/inertia).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A Newtonian unit will behave differently.
 A damped Newtonian unit will not stop as soon as the input reaches 0.
 It will gradually slow down under the effect of its internal friction (i.e.
 the viscosity of the medium).
 In practice, it will overshoot the target by a distance inversely proportional
 to its viscosity parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, an 
\emph on
undamped
\emph default
 Newtonian unit (a unity with no viscosity) will never stop.
 It will keep going indefinitely with a theoretical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

terminal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 velocity dependent on the accumulated input.
 However, given that the value of a unit (and, hence, the value of its actuator,
 i.e.
 the value of the motor command) is constrained within a Max/Min band, its
 terminal velocity will be equal to the unit's maximum value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If, instead, the setup is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Aristotelian,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but the actuator commands are either positive or negative as in the standard
 Homeo configuration, the behavior will be different and it will depend
 on the unit's initial position with respect to the gradient.
 Consider vehicle A in figure 
\begin_inset Flex ShortXRef
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Brait-like-type-1-gradient"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Its initial input will be less than 0, since it lies outside the red circle.
 Hence it will immediately move away from the input source, i.
 e.
 backward (to the left, in the diagram).
 In the absence of other stimulus sources, it will keep moving backward
 indefinitely.
 Consider instead vehicle B.
 It start within the red circle, hence its input will be positive and it
 will move forward until it crosses the red circle on the right side of
 the diagram, when its input will reach 0 and the vehicle will stop.
 In other words, the behavior is sensitive to initial conditions.
 If the starting point is past the half-way point of the gradient's value,
 the vehicle will effectively seek such a halfway point, otherwise it will
 move away from the gradient indefinitely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar consideration applies to non-Aristotelian setups.
 A damped Newtonian vehicle starting outside the red circle (case A in the
 diagram) will accelerate away and reach terminal velocity.
 A similar vehicle starting inside the red circle (case B), will overshoot
 the red circle on the opposite side, then correct backward, etcetera.
 In short it will converge harmonically on the red line on the right side
 of the diagram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally an undamped unit will accelerate away (backward) in case A, whereas
 in case B it will accelerate rigthward (forward), then reverse acceleration
 when it crosses the red line.
 It should converge on the red line as in the previous case, but with a
 much less stable behavior (i.e.
 ampler oscillations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If, on the contrary, the perceived stimulus is inversely proportional to
 the input, we would observe the reverse behavior.
 That is, the behavior will be analogous except that the target respectively
 reached or overshot will be the point in the vehicle's path where the value
 is equal to zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A true Braitenberg vehicle will keep moving as long as the input is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
zero.
 It will effectively climb up the gradient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A damped Newtonian unit will overshoot its gradient equal to zero target
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, an undamped unit will keep going---whether it reaches the terminal
 velocity equal to its max value depends on the initial distance between
 units and gradient's maximum value.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Experimental observations
\end_layout

